## **Crushed Ice vs. Chunky Cushion: The Most Important Distinction Nobody Explains**

This is the section that determines your satisfaction with a cushion cut purchase more than any other single factor — and it appears in almost no competing guide with sufficient depth.

### **What Is a Cushion Brilliant vs. Cushion Modified Brilliant?**

GIA classifies cushion cuts in two categories: **cushion brilliant** and **cushion modified brilliant**. This classification reflects the pavilion facet arrangement — but in practical buying terms, it corresponds to the chunky vs. crushed ice visual difference.

**Cushion Brilliant (Standard / "Chunky"):** The pavilion features large, broad facets radiating from the center — 4 main pavilion facets and 8 lower-half facets, similar in arrangement to a round brilliant's pavilion. These large facets produce bold, distinct flashes of light — sometimes called the "chunky" or "blocky" appearance. The light pattern is characterized by large, defined reflections that move dramatically as the stone tilts.

**Cushion Modified Brilliant ("Crushed Ice"):** The pavilion features an extra row of facets — creating a total of 8 main pavilion facets plus additional lower-half facets — that break the reflections into hundreds of smaller, more numerous light points. The result resembles crushed ice or a sparkling mosaic. The light pattern is rapid, fine-grained, and continuous rather than bold and dramatic.

![Editorial infographic comparing chunky cushion brilliant diamonds and crushed ice cushion modified diamonds with side-by-side stones, facet diagrams, and clean comparison data on a white background.](/images/cushion-brilliant-vs-cushion-modified-infographic.jpg "Cushion Brilliant Vs Cushion Modified Infographic")

### **The Visual Difference: A Practical Analogy**

Imagine a chandelier with 4 large crystal pendants versus a chandelier with 40 small crystal pendants. Both create beautiful light patterns — but one produces 4 dramatic sweeping reflections while the other produces 40 rapid sparkling points. That is the difference between chunky and crushed ice cushions.

<table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th>Visual Factor</th><th>Chunky (Standard)</th><th>Crushed Ice (Modified)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Facet size</td><td>Large, broad</td><td>Small, numerous</td></tr><tr><td>Light pattern</td><td>Bold, distinct flashes</td><td>Rapid, sparkling mosaic</td></tr><tr><td>Optical character</td><td>Vintage, romantic</td><td>Modern, brilliant</td></tr><tr><td>Inclusion hiding</td><td>Moderate — large facets can reveal inclusions</td><td>Better — small facets scatter inclusions</td></tr><tr><td>Color retention</td><td>Higher — large facets amplify body color</td><td>Lower — smaller facets diffuse color</td></tr><tr><td>Fire (colored light)</td><td>Higher</td><td>Lower</td></tr><tr><td>Brilliance (white light)</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Higher</td></tr><tr><td>GIA classification</td><td>Usually "Cushion Brilliant"</td><td>Usually "Cushion Modified Brilliant"</td></tr><tr><td>Blue Nile listing</td><td>"Cushion Diamond"</td><td>"Cushion Modified Diamond"</td></tr></tbody></table>

**How to identify which type you are looking at:** Check the Blue Nile listing description. "Cushion Diamond" typically indicates chunky standard. "Cushion Modified Diamond" indicates crushed ice modified. Always verify by watching the 360° video — the light pattern distinction is immediately obvious in motion.

Crushed ice is more popular among buyers at approximately 60% of cushion cut sales vs. 40% for chunky, but the "correct" choice is entirely personal preference. Neither is objectively superior — they serve completely different aesthetic tastes.

### **Antique Cushion (Old Mine Style): The Third Category**

![Editorial infographic explaining antique cushion diamonds with an elongated old mine style cushion diamond, side-profile proportion comparison, chunky facet illustration, and vintage-inspired feature breakdown on a white background.](/images/antique-cushion-old-mine-diamond-infographic-1.jpg "Antique Cushion Old Mine Diamond Infographic 1")

Elongated antique cushions are gaining particular traction in 2026, offering a vintage aesthetic with modern proportions. The antique cushion (also sold as "antique cushion" or "old mine inspired") features:

-   Steeper crown angles than modern cushions
-   Smaller table relative to the diamond width
-   Higher crown profile — the ring sits taller on the finger
-   Larger culet — sometimes visible as a small circle at the base when viewed through the table
-   Broader, chunkier facets that produce the most "old world" optical character

Antique cushions command a premium in specialty markets — collectors and buyers who specifically want the candlelight-era aesthetic pay more for well-executed antique proportions. For standard engagement ring buyers, modern chunky or crushed ice cushions offer better value.

## **How Many Facets Does a Cushion Cut Diamond Have?**

**A cushion cut diamond has between 58 and 64 facets depending on its style.**

![Editorial infographic explaining cushion cut diamond facet counts with chunky, modified, antique, and branded cushion diamond comparisons, showing different sparkle patterns and facet structures on a white background.](/images/cushion-cut-diamond-facet-count-infographic-1024x683.jpg "Cushion Cut Diamond Facet Count Infographic")

Cushion cuts typically comprise 58–64 facets with distinguishable curved corners.

<table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th>Style</th><th>Approximate Facet Count</th><th>Facet Pattern</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cushion Brilliant (Chunky)</td><td>58 facets</td><td>4 main pavilion facets + 8 lower-half</td></tr><tr><td>Cushion Modified Brilliant (Crushed Ice)</td><td>64+ facets</td><td>8 main pavilion facets + extra row</td></tr><tr><td>Antique Cushion (Old Mine Inspired)</td><td>58 facets</td><td>Large, broad historical pattern</td></tr><tr><td>Branded variations (X-Factor, Long Island)</td><td>64–80+ facets</td><td>Proprietary extra-facet arrangements</td></tr></tbody></table>

**Branded cushion cuts:** Some retailers and cutters sell proprietary cushion variations with trademarked names — X-Factor Cut, Long Island Cut, and others — featuring additional facets designed to maximize crushed-ice scintillation.

These are not GIA-defined categories but retailer-specific cut designs. They can produce exceptional light performance but command a premium. Evaluate them on video, not on name alone.

## **What Are the Ideal Proportions for a Cushion Cut Diamond?**

**GIA does not issue a cut grade for cushion cut diamonds — making proportion evaluation the buyer's mandatory responsibility on every single purchase.**

GIA doesn't grade cut quality for cushions, so evaluate proportions manually. When Blue Nile lists a cushion as "Ideal Cut" — that is Blue Nile's retailer grade, not a GIA laboratory certification. The same principle applies across all retailers.

### **Cushion Cut Ideal Proportion Table (2026)**

<table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th>Proportion</th><th>Ideal Range</th><th>Acceptable Range</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Table %</td><td>58–68%</td><td>55–72%</td><td>Under 52% or over 75%</td></tr><tr><td>Depth %</td><td>61–68%</td><td>59–72%</td><td>Under 57% or over 76%</td></tr><tr><td>Length-to-Width Ratio (Square)</td><td>1.00–1.05</td><td>1.00–1.09</td><td>Over 1.12 (noticeably rectangular)</td></tr><tr><td>Length-to-Width Ratio (Elongated)</td><td>1.15–1.30</td><td>1.10–1.40</td><td>Under 1.08 looks square, over 1.45 extreme</td></tr><tr><td>Girdle</td><td>Thin–Slightly Thick</td><td>Very Thin–Thick</td><td>Extremely Thin or Extremely Thick</td></tr><tr><td>Culet</td><td>None / Pointed</td><td>Very Small</td><td>Medium or larger (visible dot through table)</td></tr><tr><td>Polish</td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td></tr><tr><td>Symmetry</td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **The Depth Warning: Avoiding a "Leaky" Cushion**

A cushion cut with depth over 72% has a deep pavilion that "leaks" light — light enters through the table and exits through the sides and bottom rather than reflecting back up to the observer's eye. The result is a stone that appears darker and less brilliant than a well-proportioned cushion at identical carat weight, clarity, and color.

A depth over 75% also produces a "nail-head" effect — a dark, shadowy center visible when looking through the table. This is caused by steep pavilion angles redirecting light at incorrect angles.

**Practical rule:** On the GIA certificate, verify depth % is under 68% before purchasing. Anything over 70% requires video verification to confirm no leakage.

### **The Table Warning: When Smaller Is Better**

Unlike round brilliants where a 56–58% table is optimal, cushion cuts perform best with a slightly smaller table (58–68%). A table over 72% in a cushion creates a "window" effect — the stone becomes transparent and you can see through it rather than seeing reflections. A table under 52% produces insufficient light entry. The 58–68% range balances brilliance and fire specific to cushion geometry.

### **The Girdle Warning: High Girdle = Tall Setting**

A cushion cut with thick to extremely thick girdle sits tall on a halo setting — the jeweler may not be able to set it lower because of the thick girdle. Always verify girdle thickness on the GIA certificate. For halo settings specifically — the most popular cushion setting — a medium girdle (Thin to Slightly Thick) allows the stone to sit lower and more securely in the halo.

### **What Is the Ideal L/W Ratio for Square vs. Elongated Cushion?**

![Editorial infographic showing ideal cushion cut diamond proportions with side-view geometry diagrams, light leakage comparison, and a clean 2026 proportion table on a white background.](/images/ideal-proportions-cushion-cut-diamond-infographic-1024x683.jpg "Ideal Proportions Cushion Cut Diamond Infographic")

**Square cushion:** 1.00–1.05 for the most balanced, symmetrical square appearance. For the optimal length-to-width ratio of a square cushion, aim for 1.00–1.09. Over 1.10 begins to read as rectangular to the naked eye.

**Elongated cushion:** 1.15–1.30 is the current sweet spot. Elongated antique cushions — the 2026 trending variation — typically run 1.20–1.35. The most popular slight rectangle has a length 1.10–1.20 times the width. The elongated cushion provides a finger-lengthening effect similar to oval but with the cushion's softer, rounded corner aesthetic.

Use the **[diamond size chart](https://diamondcritics.com/diamond-size-chart/)** to understand how L/W ratio affects the physical dimensions you actually see on the finger.

