<table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th>Buyer Scenario</th><th>Farzana's Rule</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Vintage aesthetic buyer</td><td><strong>Chunky cushion, H-G color, VS2</strong></td><td>Large facets maximize fire and vintage character</td></tr><tr><td>Modern sparkle buyer</td><td><strong>Crushed ice (modified), H-VS2</strong></td><td>Smaller facets produce round-brilliant-like scintillation</td></tr><tr><td>Active lifestyle buyer</td><td><strong>Cushion over princess — no corner risk</strong></td><td>Rounded corners have zero structural vulnerability</td></tr><tr><td>Budget-maximizing buyer</td><td><strong>Cushion H-VS2, depth under 68%</strong></td><td>$1,770 entry, best value brilliant shape for square preference</td></tr><tr><td>Large stone buyer (2ct+)</td><td><strong>Lab-grown D-IF GCAL, 2.38ct at $9,740</strong></td><td>Extraordinary value vs $10,470+ natural</td></tr><tr><td>Maximum size illusion buyer</td><td><strong>Elongated cushion, L/W 1.20–1.30</strong></td><td>Elongated outline provides some finger-lengthening effect</td></tr><tr><td>Fancy color diamond buyer</td><td><strong>Always cushion</strong></td><td>Optimum color retention for yellow, pink, blue</td></tr><tr><td>Yellow gold ring buyer</td><td><strong>H-I color acceptable</strong></td><td>Yellow metal masks body color — save on color, invest in cut</td></tr></tbody></table>

## **Rapid-Fire FAQs: The Complete Cushion Cut Masterclass**

### **What does cushion cut mean in diamonds?**

A cushion cut diamond is a square or rectangular diamond with rounded corners and curved sides, resembling a cushion or pillow. The name comes directly from its silhouette. It is formally classified by GIA as "cushion brilliant" or "cushion modified brilliant" depending on pavilion facet arrangement.

It is the third most popular engagement ring shape in 2026 and the most historically significant — evolving from the Old Mine Cut dominant from the 1700s through the early 1900s.

### **Is a cushion cut diamond more expensive than round?**

No — cushion cuts cost approximately 25–45% less than round brilliants at equivalent quality specifications. In **May** 2026, a 1ct natural H-VS2 Ideal Cut cushion modified starts at **[$1,770](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27404713?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** versus $3,200 for a comparable round brilliant — a $1,430 saving.

The price difference exists because round brilliant cutting wastes approximately 50% of rough diamond while cushion cutting wastes far less.

### **What is the difference between a cushion brilliant and a cushion modified brilliant?**

A cushion brilliant has 4 main pavilion facets — producing large, bold flashes (chunky appearance). A cushion modified brilliant has 8 main pavilion facets plus an additional row — producing fine, rapid scintillation (crushed ice appearance). Both are GIA-recognized subcategories of cushion cut.

Blue Nile lists them as "Cushion Diamond" (standard) and "Cushion Modified Diamond" (modified). They look completely different in person — always watch the 360° video.

### **What is a crushed ice cushion and why do some buyers avoid it?**

A crushed ice cushion is a cushion modified brilliant with small, numerous facets producing a sparkling mosaic pattern similar to a handful of crushed ice.

Some buyers avoid it because: it lacks the distinctive bold fire flashes of a chunky cushion (the primary reason to choose cushion over round), it can appear "busy" or "commercial" in lower-quality executions, and it shows inclusions slightly differently than chunky facets.

Crushed ice is more popular at approximately 60% of cushion sales — but buyers who specifically love the vintage cushion aesthetic almost always prefer chunky.

### **What is the ideal depth and table percentage for a cushion cut diamond?**

Ideal table: 58–68%. Ideal depth: 61–68%. Depths over 70% produce leakage and potential nail-head effects. Tables over 73% create window effects where the stone appears transparent rather than reflective.

Always verify both on the GIA certificate before purchasing any cushion cut. GIA does not grade cushion cut quality — these proportions are your manual evaluation tool.

### **Do cushion cut diamonds chip easily?**

No — cushion cuts are among the most durable popular engagement ring shapes. The rounded corners have no structural weak points. Compare this to the **[princess cut](https://diamondcritics.com/princess-cut-diamond/)** where four sharp 90-degree corners are the most common source of diamond chipping in engagement rings.

Cushion cuts can be set in any standard prong configuration without the V-prong requirement that princess cuts demand.

### **Are cushion cut rings out of style?**

No — cushion cuts are timeless. Unlike the princess cut which peaked in the 2000s and has been declining, cushion cuts have maintained consistent popularity across decades because of their historical heritage and romantic aesthetic.

Elongated antique cushion shapes are gaining particular traction in 2026 — making the cushion category currently in a growth phase rather than a decline. They are not trend-sensitive in the same way as princess cuts.

### **Why does the cushion cut require a higher color grade than round brilliant?**

Cushion cuts retain body color more visibly than round brilliants because their larger facets allow the stone's body color to be seen rather than being overridden by white light reflections.

A G-color round appears virtually colorless in a white gold setting. A G-color chunky cushion may show faint warmth at the corners in direct overhead lighting. The minimum recommended color for a white metal cushion solitaire is G — with H acceptable for crushed ice style.

See the **[G color guide](https://diamondcritics.com/g-color-diamond/)** and **[H color guide](https://diamondcritics.com/h-color-diamond/)** for full comparison data.

### **How does 1ct cushion cut price compare to 1ct oval in 2026?**

A 1ct H-VS2 cushion modified starts at $1,770 in **May** 2026. A 1ct G-VS1 oval starts at approximately $2,800. The oval commands approximately $1,030 more for the same approximate quality — the premium buys a 10–15% larger face-up appearance and the finger-lengthening effect of the oval's elongated outline.

For buyers who want more apparent size, the oval is worth the premium. For buyers who prefer the square-ish outline, the cushion delivers superior value.

### **What is the best setting for a cushion cut diamond?**

The most popular and most versatile cushion cut setting is the round halo with pavé band — it maximizes apparent size, adds scintillation, and the circular halo complements the cushion's rounded outline. For vintage aesthetics: milgrain solitaire or bezel with filigree band.

For maximum diamond visibility: four-prong solitaire. For elongated cushions (L/W over 1.15): double-claw prongs at the long ends for extra security. For active lifestyles: bezel setting for corner-free maximum protection.


## **Final Verdict: Should You Buy a Cushion Cut Diamond?**

The cushion cut is the right choice for a specific, well-defined buyer — and for that buyer, it delivers everything they need at prices 25–45% below round brilliant.

**Buy a cushion cut if:** You love vintage-romantic aesthetics. You want fire over brilliance. You prioritize durability over maximum visual size. You want a historically significant, timeless shape that will never look dated. You are buying lab-grown at 2ct+ — the arbitrage is exceptional.

**Understand before you buy:** GIA does not grade cushion cut quality — manual proportion verification is mandatory. Crushed ice and chunky look completely different — decide which you prefer before searching. Color retention is real — G minimum in white gold, H acceptable in yellow gold. Dense clouds in SI1 cushions can ruin light performance regardless of grade.

> 
> 
> "The cushion cut is the diamond shape with the most soul. Its rounded corners carry 300 years of jewelry history. Its fire — the colored light dispersion that makes it different from round — is the most romantic optical effect in the market. But it demands a more educated buyer than any other shape: GIA will not grade the cut for you, the crushed ice vs. chunky decision will determine your daily happiness, and the color retention science requires a higher grade than round buyers need. Buy a cushion cut knowing all of this, and you will own one of the most beautiful rings in any room." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**
